  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Emerson Electric generated <strong>${fcfBase !== null ? (fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} billion</strong> in free cash flow recently. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, including capital expenditures required to maintain and grow its operations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. This reflects a conservative growth expectation for an established industrial technology and software company as it continues its portfolio transformation towards automation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong> — slightly below long-term GDP growth, acknowledging the mature nature of the industrial sector while giving credit to EMR's enduring competitive position. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</strong> — our required rate of return. This is calculated using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) utilizing a {(riskFreeRate * 100).toFixed(2)}% risk-free rate and EMR's beta.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash !== null ? (netCash / 1000).toFixed(1) : 'N/A'}B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding !== null ? (sharesOutstanding / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Emerson is transitioning into a higher-growth, higher-margin automation portfolio (e.g., acquiring NI). While historical revenue growth has been mixed due to divestitures, the new core is positioned to grow faster. 8% FCF growth balances optimism for the new portfolio with the cyclical realities of industrial end-markets.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: {(riskFreeRate * 100).toFixed(2)}%. Equity risk premium: {(equityRiskPremium * 100).toFixed(1)}%. Beta: {beta !== null ? beta.toFixed(2) : '1.20'}. CAPM derives our cost of equity around {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%. This compensates investors for the risk of holding EMR compared to a risk-free bond.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is typically around 2-3%. A 2.5% terminal growth rate assumes Emerson maintains its market position in global automation and grows roughly in line with the global economy in perpetuity.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

