  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks and Limitations</h2>
  <p>No model is perfectly predictive. Here are factors that could skew this valuation:</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Synergy Realization:</strong> If Emerson extracts more cost or revenue synergies from recent acquisitions (like NI) than anticipated, margins and FCF growth could exceed 8%.</li>
    <li><strong>Industrial Reshoring:</strong> A faster-than-expected macro trend of reshoring manufacturing to North America could drive sustained above-trend demand for automation.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> If the company utilizes excess cash flow for massive share repurchases at undervalued prices, per-share value will increase mechanically.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Integration Missteps:</strong> EMR has undergone a massive portfolio transformation. Failure to effectively integrate large acquisitions could lead to value destruction.</li>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> Despite moving toward more software/automation, industrial end-markets remain cyclical. A severe global recession would compress near-term cash flows heavily.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher Cost of Capital:</strong> If inflation proves sticky and interest rates remain structurally higher for longer, the appropriate discount rate would rise, lowering intrinsic value.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use FCF instead of Net Income?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Free Cash Flow is harder to manipulate than Net Income. Net Income includes non-cash depreciation and amortization, and ignores capital expenditures needed to sustain the business. For an acquisitive industrial company like EMR, FCF is a purer measure of the actual cash available to shareholders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the recent portfolio transformation affect this model?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">By focusing on forward-looking cash flow projections rather than purely extrapolating the past, this DCF attempts to value the "new" Emerson—a higher-margin automation player—rather than the legacy conglomerate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value based on a specific set of assumptions. It is for educational purposes. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio strategy, and independent due diligence.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

